White wine exploration by Stefan Langenbach

Udacity data analyst nanodegree

The dataset we are going to investigate consists of roughly 4.900 records of white wines and 12 attributes specifying their (chemical) properties, i.e.acidity, pH-level, alcohol-percentage and quality rating. Each wine was rated by at least 3 experts in order to provide a quality score. The score ranges from 0 (worst) to 10 (best).

## [1] 0

Investigating summary statistics for our dataset, it is obvious that some of the variables contain extreme values. For example: The maximum value for residual sugar is roughly 12.5 times the median. Other variables containing extreme values are chlorides (maximum value is roughly 8 times median value), and free.sulfur.dioxide. Another interesting insight is that no wine reached the maximum quality rating of 10.

Univariate Plots Section

Lets move on with a visual investigation of our dataset. The following plots will investigate each variable individually.

Non-chemical variables

Wine rating ranges from 3 to 9 and most wines were given a rating of 6. There are only very few wines with particularly bad (quality = 3) or good (quality = 9) ratings.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    8.00    9.50   10.40   10.51   11.40   14.20

The distribution of percentage of alcohol of wines in the dataset is multi-modal. Although most wines have between 9 and 9.5% of alcohol, there are more peaks 10.5, close to 11 and close to 12.5.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.2200  0.4100  0.4700  0.4898  0.5500  1.0800

Interestingly, sulphates has a bi-modal distribution with peaks at about 0.375 and 0.475. Furthermore there are few wines with high values of sulphates (above 0.85).

pH values seem to be almost normally distributed with a peak at 3.15. The distribution has a longer tail at the right side.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.600   1.700   5.200   6.391   9.900  65.800

As already observed during investigation of summary statistics, residual.sugar contains extreme values, thus skewing standard plots without scaling of the x-axis. The plot above uses a log10-scaled x-axis and provides better insight into the distribution of residual sugar. It appears to be multi-modal with peaks at roughly 1.75, 8 and 14.

Most wines have a density close to 1.

Chemical variables

Lets also investigate the remaining chemical variables:

  • fixed.acidity
  • volatile.acidity
  • citric.acid
  • chlorides
  • free.sulfur.dioxide
  • total.sulfur.dioxide

For most wines fixed acidity lies between 6 and 7.25 with two peaks at 6.5 and 7.25

Volatile acidity peaks at roughly 0.25 for most wines, but there are two additional plateaus at about 0.2 and 0.3.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0000  0.2700  0.3200  0.3342  0.3900  1.6600

Majority of wines have a concentration of citric acid ranging from 0.25 to 0.35. The maximum value is 1.66, which is roughly 5 times the median.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.00900 0.03600 0.04300 0.04577 0.05000 0.34600

Similar to residual.sugar, chlorides contains extreme values, thus skewing standard plots without scaling of the x-axis. The plot above uses a log10-scaled x-axis and provides better insight into the distribution of chlorides. Most wines have concentration of chlorides between 0.03 and 0.06.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.00   23.00   34.00   35.31   46.00  289.00

Also free sulfur dioxide contains extreme values and thus the x-axis has been scaled to log10. Most wines have concentration of free sulfur dioxides between 25 and 50.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     9.0   108.0   134.0   138.4   167.0   440.0

Most wines contain between 100 and 150mg of sulfur dioxide. There is one wine with a value three more than 3 time the median, i.e.440.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset contains roughly 4.900 observations and 12 variables (X is just an index). The variable quality is an ordered factor ranging from 0 (worst) to 10 (best).

Additional observations:

  • No wine has a quality rating below 3, none has one above 9
  • Most wines contain between 9 and 11% of alcohol
  • Median for residual sugar is 5.2g, but there is one wine with 65g
  • Sulphates has a bi-modal distribution

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features to predict quality should be alcohol, residual sugar and sulphates.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

A combination of pure chemical features, i.e.free sulfur dioxide, chlorides and some measure of acidity, could also have an effect on quality

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created factors for my main variables of interest (alcohol, residual sugar and sulphates) using cut with break points

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Some of the variables had bi- or multi-modal distributions, i.e.sulphates and

residual sugar. In order to get an better overview about the distribution I transformed the x-axis of their plots to log10.

Bivariate Plots Section and analysis

Before investigating relationships among the main features of the dataset and wine quality, let us check correlations among all variables:

Apparently there exist only a moderately strong positive correlation between quality and alcohol. All other variables seem to be either unrelated or moderately negatively correlated (density) with quality. Consequently I will limit my bivariate analysis to relationships between

  • quality and alcohol
  • quality and density
  • density and alcohol
  • density and residual sugar

Generally we can observe a moderate trend of rising levels of alcohol concentration given increasing quality ratings. Although alcohol concentration decreases when moving from quality ratings of 3 to those of 4 and 5, the existence of outliers for these quality ratings indicates that there exists a slight positive trend.

The further quality ratings increase, the lower density becomes.

Both scatter plots visualize what has been revealed by the correlation matrix: Strong negative/positive relationships between density and alcohol/residual sugar

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

As the correlation matrix revealed, only quality and alcohol have a moderate positive relationship.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

There is a strong positive relationship between density and residual sugar, as well as a strong negative relationship between density and alcohol. The latter makes sense to me, given the explanation from wineQualityInfo.txt: the density of wine is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content. Therefore, as alcohol concentration increases, density decreases.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

As mentioned above, the strongest correlations (+/- 0.8) are those between density and alcohol and density and residual.

Lets have a look at the relationship between alcohol, quality and density:

If we inspect the plot closely we do see higher concentrations of alcohol associated with higher quality rating and lower values for density.

Multivariate Analysis

Model is based on the assumptions I outlined in the univariate plots section, i.e.that alcohol, sulphates and residual sugar would be predictors of quality, and the insights from the correlation matrix. The results show, that a model solely based on alcohol is equally good (or worse taking into account adjusted R^2 values of roughly only 0.22 (lm1), 0.19 (lm2), 0.21 (lm3) and 0.19 (lm4).

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The majority of wines in the dataset is rated between 5 and 7, with 6 being the most frequent rating. Wines included in average to above-average rating categories (>= 6) tend to have a higher concentration of alcohol.

Plot Two

Description Two

Building on the insights of plot one, plot two clearly shows that median values of alcohol concentration are rising with higher quality ratings. Rating categories 4 and 5 do include a fair amount of outliers.

Plot Three

Description Three

The correlation matrix clearly shows that quality is only really correlated with alcohol and density. All other variables are not correlated with quality.

Reflection

When reflecting on my analysis of the wine dataset, the following points come to mind:

Path of analysis

I started by examining every single variable in the dataset and formulated hypotheses on which variables could be significant in predicting wine quality. After calculating correlations, I found out that actually only alcohol (and density) had some correlation with quality. Therefore I based my linear models on these variables (and the factors I created from them).

Challlenges

  • As most of the (chemical) variables of the wine dataset were unknown to me, before starting with data exploration, I had familiarize myself with their meaning
  • In the beginning I used histograms for every visualization in univariate analysis and played with bin width. I realized only later that freqpoly plots have some advantage of histograms when the variable of interest is dispersed over a wide range of values
  • It took me some time to best deal with log10 transformed x-axis

Successes

  • The correlation matrix I created with ggcorr was very helpful for further analysis.
  • I found geom_smooth() to be very helpful in visualizing trends in the data.

Surprising observations

  • Before starting my analysis, that the dataset would contain more variables that were highly correlated with wine quality. It was a bit disappointing to have only alcohol to play with.

Recommendations for future work

  • It would be great to incorporate further (economic) variables (price, quantity sold, origin of wine, etc.) into the dataset to investigate quality from a different angle.
